Democracy without Popular Cohesion
In a sense, democracy is that the government is elected by the people and taken over, and this happens worldwide.
Somewhere along the way, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout has declined in many countries; in the case of European Parliament elections, the turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Besides voter turnout, we have gotten used to considering parties or candidates who received 25% of the votes as "winners."
From Holland to Finland, and from Argentina to Japan, governments are formed based on minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the contrary.
Only a few American presidents were elected by more than 10% of the voting-eligible population. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the USA do not even register to vote; of those who do register, half do not actually vote; and of those who do vote, less than half vote for the winner.
Even Tony Blair's "avalanche-like" majority in the UK House of Commons stands on shaky ground: the Labour Party received only slightly more than 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, at a voter turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look quite different today compared to twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
A possible answer is that voters no longer trust political parties.
Most democracies rely on organizations that put forward candidates advocating for specific packages of political options, a "manifesto" or "election program."
This time-tested practice is no longer working for several reasons.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the bundled packages offered by parties, they want to reach out and choose for themselves.
Moreover, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized cliques of insiders.
The paradox here is that parties have become even more cliquey despite losing their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated parties from the electorate.
Because most people don't want to belong to any particular party, only a minority now plays the party game.
Thus, public mistrust of political parties also increases in part because, like in professional sports, it's expensive to play – especially when the costs are paid by taxpayers.
If the costs are borne by taxpayers, it is resented.
Without financial support from the state, parties would have to find money through channels that are often questionable, if not outright illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of recent decades involved the financing of parties and their candidates.
Andere Indizien - wie das deutliche Nachlassen der Mitgliedschaften - bestätigen, dass die Parteien unpopulär geworden sind.
Dennoch sind Parteien für eine Wahldemokratie unentbehrlich.
Das Ergebnis ist eine offensichtliche Trennung zwischen den sichtbaren politischen Akteuren und der Wählerschaft.
Weil die Parteien in den Parlamenten tätig sind, betreffen die Auswirkungen dieser Trennung eine der entscheidenden Einrichtungen der Demokratie.
Leute glauben nicht mehr, dass die Parlamente sie vertreten und dadurch mit der nötigen Legitimität ausgestattet sind, an ihrer Stelle Entscheidungen zu fällen.
An diesem Punkt kommt eine zweite, ziemlich unabhängige Entwicklung ins Spiel.
Die Menschen sind heute ungeduldiger als je zuvor.
Als Verbraucher sind sie an eine sofortige Zufriedenstellung gewöhnt.
Doch müssen sie als Wähler warten, ehe sie die Ergebnisse der Wahl zu spüren bekommen, die sie an der Wahlurne getroffen haben.
Manchmal sehen sie niemals die gewünschten Ergebnisse.
The democracy needs time not only for elections but also for discussions and careful weighing.
The consumer as a voter does not want to wait and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. But each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "Direct Action" through demonstrations has become a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet discussion pages to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet they seem to be more closely connected to citizens.
In addition, there is of course the option of completely switching off and leaving politics to the experts, focusing instead on other aspects of life.
However, the latter harbors the greatest risks, as it fosters creeping authoritarianism, which is a hallmark of our time.
But the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also create a very insecure situation, as nobody can say anymore how representative the prevailing views are.
Some want to tackle the knot through more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and led cannot be established by reducing public debate to simple voting alternatives.
There is still much to be said for holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to re-establish closer connections with the citizenry.
Unpopular parties and declining voter turnout might turn out to be only temporary phenomena.
New parties could emerge and breathe new life into elections and representative governments.
But this may likely not be sufficient to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Daher muss das erste Anliegen aller, denen die Verfassung der Freiheit am Herzen liegt, sein, sich die Demokratie und ihre Institutionen neu auszudenken.
